{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515703"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12487"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12487"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.05,0.04,0.28,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50430"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4994"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12487"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35652"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"3758"},{"type":"tags","id":"12095"},{"type":"tags","id":"12908"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50430"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a fever and general malaise. She has a medical history of metastatic breast cancer and hyperlipidaemia. Her current medications are paclitaxel, trastuzumab and atorvastatin. She also uses ondansetron on an as-needed basis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 25/min, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. She is alert and oriented and appears comfortable. She has warm peripheries, her chest is clear, and her abdomen is non-tender. She has no skin wounds or evidence of cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations will be most useful in guiding management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Full blood count","Chest X-ray","C-reactive protein","Blood cultures","Urine microscopy and culture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient likely has neutropenic sepsis, given her history of ongoing chemotherapy and high fever. This is an oncological emergency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efull blood count\u003C/strong\u003E will confirm her absolute neutrophil count (ANC) and confirm this diagnosis. Determining whether this patient is at risk of sepsis versus neutropenic sepsis changes the antibiotic choice and is hence crucial to immediate patient management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe definition of febrile neutropenia is an ANC of \u003C 0.5 x 10^9/L or an ANC of \u003C 1.0 x 10^9/L and predicted to deteriorate to \u003C0.5 x 10^9/L within 48 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFebrile neutropenia should be treated with aggressive broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy (e.g. piperacillin/tazobactam) after blood cultures have been taken.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of a septic screen to identify the source of infection, but not the most important test given the patient\u0027s history and lack of respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute phase reactant that can be elevated in various inflammatory conditions, including infections. While it may be elevated in this patient, it is not specific enough to guide management in suspected neutropenic sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are indeed a crucial investigation to identify the pathogenic organism and guide antibiotic therapy. These should be taken from all access sites (e.g. including permanent port sites). However, the full blood count is still more immediately useful in confirming neutropenia and guiding initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in identifying a urinary source of infection. However, in this case, there are no specific urinary symptoms, and confirming neutropenia takes priority in guiding immediate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neutropenic sepsis is an oncological emergency confirmed with full blood count (ANC \u003C 0.5)","Blood cultures are crucial in the identification of the organism causing neutropenic sepsis"],"references":["National Collaborating Centre for Cancer (UK). Neutropenic Sepsis: Prevention and Management of Neutropenic Sepsis in Cancer Patients. London: National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence (NICE); 2012 Sep. (NICE Clinical Guidelines, No. 151.) 2, Diagnosis of neutropenic sepsis. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK373673/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35652"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12487"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35652"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-11T20:30:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-11T20:32:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4994"}},"content":{"data"